Love has several different meanings in the [[English (language)|English]] language, from something that gives a little pleasure ("I loved that meal") to something that one would die for ([[patriotism]], [[pair-bonding]]). And in contrast to the definition at the top, frequently people use the verb "love" to indicate want or desire for themselves as opposed to for another. For example: "I love ice cream," or even "I love her/him," does not refer to desiring wellness for ice cream, and it may not refer to desiring wellness for her/him, but rather to the desire for ice cream or for her/him felt by the speaker. The word also frequently indicates elevated appreciation or admiration: "I love that artist."
